===from:Nick, Jennifer, Rick, Janessa, and Laura
===date:Sun Dec 13 17:49:15 1998
===subject:Biodiversity Assignment
===message:Nick Boyd, Jennifer Johnson, Rik Monserud, Janessa A. Morgan, and Laura Nosbisch--We were unsatisfied with each of the scenarios listed.  This is why we chose to come up with what we see as a much more viable alternative.  Our scenario is as follows:  8 billion humans whose standard of living is slowly progressing toward the equivalent of current-day "developed" countries(not having completely reached that point yet, allowing "less developed" countries to remain so until they choose to become more developed).  Approxomately 60% of the current-day biodiversity remains on Earth, including all species that are currently used by humans for food, fuel, fiber, or pharmacueticals, as well as some additional species used by humans in some new way.  We feel that by implementing a strong contraceptive awareness program with as limited reproductive regulation as possible, we an slow the exploding population growth without killing people off.  We also felt an ever-present need to maintain as much biodiversity as possible while allowing countries to become "developed" so they can learn to utilize materials more efficiently.  With the presence of the "developed" countries, we will have more resources for advancing the future of Planet Earth within our grasp so humans can one day learn to live harmoniously with the surrounding biodiversity, whether useful to them or not.
=========yorg=========
===from:John Hamre, Skip Bouma, Lawrence Cunningham, Angi Grengs, Andrea Rasmusson
===date:Sun Dec 13 18:18:47 1998
===subject:Scenario 2
===message:Defense:  We choose scenario two because it is the most realistic of the four choices.  People wouldn’t be able to handle lowering their standards of living no matter how gradual it is.  If we start declining now we will continue to decline.  People would lose faith and not have a reason to live for.  This makes scenario 1 and 3 impractical choices.   Situation four would not work unless there was some massive catastrophe.  It is unrealistic to cut the current population in half. 
	As far as biodiversity, at the rate things are going ten percent seems to be a realistic number.  Although this is unfortunate it is necessary to continue to live the life we are living now.  In order for the human species to survive other species are going to have to be sacrificed.

